# StyleDrop React E-Commerce - Architecture & Guidelines

## Project Overview
Modern e-commerce React application built with Vite, React Router, TypeScript, Tailwind CSS, and shadcn/ui. Designed for Shopify Liquid conversion.

## Tech Stack
- **Framework:** React 18 + TypeScript
- **Build Tool:** Vite
- **Routing:** React Router DOM v6
- **Styling:** Tailwind CSS + shadcn/ui + CSS custom properties
- **State:** Local component state (useState), TanStack React Query configured
- **Fonts:** Bebas Neue (display), Inter (body), Barlow Condensed (labels)

## Project Structure

### Folder Organization
```
src/
├── pages/              # Route-level pages (Index, Collection, ProductDetails, BrandProducts, NotFound)
├── layouts/            # Layout wrappers (MainLayout with Header/Footer)
├── sections/           # Large page sections (Hero, Trending, Categories, etc.)
├── components/         # Reusable UI components (ProductCard, ProductGrid, etc.)
│   └── ui/             # shadcn/ui library (40+ components)
├── data/               # Mock data (products, brands, testimonials)
├── types/              # TypeScript type definitions
├── hooks/              # Custom React hooks
└── assets/             # Images and static files
```

### Current Routes
- `/` → Index (Home page)
- `/collection` → Collection (Product catalog)
- `/product/:id` → ProductDetails (Single product page)
- `/brand/:brandName` → BrandProducts (Brand-specific products)
- `*` → NotFound (404)

## Pages

### 1. Index (Home) - `/`
**Sections (in order):**
- HeroSection - Hero banner with trust features, CTA buttons
- BrandsSection - Brand showcase carousel (clickable to brand pages)
- TrendingSection - Trending products (clickable to product details)
- CategoryGridSection - Category navigation
- SaleBanner - Promotional banner
- LifestyleBanners - Lifestyle images
- TestimonialsSection - Customer reviews
- NewsletterSection - Email signup

### 2. Collection - `/collection`
Product catalog with filtering, sorting, pagination.
- Breadcrumb navigation
- Collection header (title, sort, view toggle)
- FilterSidebar (left) - Categories, price, size, colors, brands
- ProductGrid (right) - Responsive product cards
- Load more functionality

### 3. ProductDetails - `/product/:id`
Single product page with full details.
- Breadcrumb navigation (Home > Brand > Product)
- Image gallery with thumbnails (4 images)
- Product info panel (title, rating, price, description)
- Color swatches, size selector, quantity
- Add to cart button
- Feature icons (shipping, returns, stock)
- Collapsible accordions (Size Guide, Shipping, Fabric & Care, FAQ, Return Policy)
- Related products section

### 4. BrandProducts - `/brand/:brandName`
Brand-specific product collection.
- Brand hero header with background, badge, name
- Brand stats (rating, reviews, product count)
- Brand description
- FilterSidebar and ProductGrid (same as Collection)
- Sort and view options

## Reusable Components

### Core Layout
**MainLayout** - Wraps all pages
- Props: `children: ReactNode`
- Includes: Header (promo bar, nav, cart) + Footer (links, brand info)

### Product Components
**ProductCard** - Single product display (clickable to ProductDetails)
- Props: `product: Product`
- Features: Image, badges, wishlist, add-to-cart, color swatches, pricing

**ProductGrid** - Responsive product grid
- Props: `products: Product[]`, `columns?: 2 | 3 | 4`
- Default: 3 columns (2 mobile, 3 desktop)

**FilterSidebar** - Complete filtering UI
- Features: Categories, price range, sizes, colors, availability, brands
- All sections collapsible

**CategoryCard** - Category navigation card (clickable to /collection)
- Props: `category: Category`
- Features: Background image, overlay, hover zoom

### Section Components
- **HeroSection** - Hero banner with CTA buttons (linked to /collection)
- **BrandsSection** - Brand carousel (cards link to /brand/:brandName)
- **TrendingSection** - Featured products (cards link to /product/:id)
- **CategoryGridSection** - Category grid
- **SaleBanner** - Promotional banner (CTA links to /collection)
- **LifestyleBanners** - Lifestyle image grid
- **TestimonialsSection** - Customer testimonials
- **NewsletterSection** - Email signup

### UI Components (shadcn/ui)
Available at `@/components/ui/`: Button, Card, Input, Checkbox, Select, Dialog, Sheet, Accordion, Tabs, Carousel, Badge, Separator, Alert, Avatar, Calendar, Command, Dropdown, Form, Hover Card, Label, Menubar, Navigation Menu, Pagination, Popover, Progress, Radio Group, Scroll Area, Skeleton, Slider, Switch, Table, Textarea, Toast, Toggle, Tooltip

## Styling System

### Approach
Tailwind CSS with custom design tokens via CSS variables (HSL-based).

### Custom Utility Classes
- `.heading-stretch-up` - Vertical text stretch (scaleY 1.45)
- `.section-dark` - Dark section styling
- `.badge-accent` - Red accent badge
- `.btn-accent` - Red accent button
- `.btn-outline-light` - Outlined button for dark backgrounds

### Brand Colors
- **Primary:** `#0D0D0D` (black)
- **Accent:** `#DC2626` (red)
- **Yellow:** `#F5C800` (badges)
- **Cream:** `#F5F0EB` (backgrounds)

### Typography
- **Display (Headings):** Bebas Neue
- **Body:** Inter
- **Labels/Badges:** Barlow Condensed

### Container
- Max-width: 1141px (Figma design)
- Centered with 2rem padding

## Data & Types

### Mock Data (`src/data/`)
- **products.ts** - `collectionProducts` array
- **brands.ts** - `featuredBrands` array
- **testimonials.ts** - Customer reviews

### Type Definitions (`src/types/index.ts`)
```typescript
Product: { id?, img, brand, name, price, originalPrice?, colors, badge?, badgeType?, rating?, reviewCount? }
Brand: { name, color, logo?, tagline? }
Category: { name, img, span?, link? }
Testimonial: { name, text, rating, avatar?, date? }
FilterOption: { name, count?, active? }
TrustFeature: { icon, title, description }
```

## Navigation Flow

### Homepage Links
- **Hero "Shop What's Trending"** → `/collection`
- **Hero "Explore New Arrivals"** → `/collection`
- **Brand Cards** → `/brand/:brandName`
- **Trending Product Cards** → `/product/:id`
- **Category Cards** → `/collection`
- **Sale Banner CTA** → `/collection`
- **All section "View all" links** → `/collection`

### Product Pages
- **ProductCard (anywhere)** → `/product/:id` (or `/product/:slug`)
- **Brand name in ProductDetails** → `/brand/:brandName`

### Brand Pages
- **Brand cards in BrandsSection** → `/brand/:brandName`
- Filters products by brand name

## Best Practices

### Component Reuse
1. **Always use MainLayout** for consistent header/footer
2. **Import and reuse** existing components before creating new ones
3. **Use shadcn/ui components** for forms, modals, tabs, etc.
4. **Use Link from react-router-dom** instead of `<a>` tags for internal navigation

### Styling
1. **Follow Tailwind utility-first** approach
2. **Use font-display class** for headings (Bebas Neue)
3. **Use container class** for max-width constraints
4. **Use custom utility classes** (.btn-accent, .badge-accent, .heading-stretch-up)

### TypeScript
1. **Import types** from `@/types` for type safety
2. **Define component props** with TypeScript interfaces
3. **Use optional props** with default values

### Shopify Liquid Readiness
1. **Keep HTML structure clean** - avoid complex React state for UI toggles when CSS classes can handle it
2. **Use simple conditional rendering** - easier to convert to Liquid conditionals
3. **Avoid inline arrow functions** in JSX where possible for cleaner Liquid conversion
4. **Comment component purpose** at the top of each file with Shopify mapping

### State Management
- **Local state only** - use `useState` for component-level state
- **No global state** - keep it simple (no Redux/Zustand)
- **React Query available** but not actively used (configured for future API calls)

## Quick Start Template

### New Page Component
```typescript
import MainLayout from '@/layouts/MainLayout';
import { Link } from 'react-router-dom';

const NewPage = () => {
  return (
    <MainLayout>
      <div className="container py-8">
        <h1 className="font-display text-5xl">PAGE TITLE</h1>
        {/* Content here */}
      </div>
    </MainLayout>
  );
};

export default NewPage;
```

### Adding New Route
1. Create page component in `src/pages/`
2. Import in `App.tsx`
3. Add `<Route path="/new-path" element={<NewPage />} />` in `<Routes>`

## Component Priority
1. **Layout:** MainLayout → Header/Footer
2. **Products:** ProductGrid → ProductCard
3. **Sections:** Import from `@/sections/`
4. **UI:** Use shadcn/ui from `@/components/ui/`
5. **Custom:** Create only when needed

# Valgara Pattern Guide for React -> Shopify Conversion

## What Is the Valgara Pattern?

The **Valgara Pattern** is a strict conversion architecture used to migrate a React/Tailwind storefront into a Shopify theme without losing design fidelity.

Its core idea is simple:

- **Liquid files should not contain Tailwind utility styling.**
- **Each converted component gets isolated, scoped CSS in its own asset file.**
- **Styling is controlled by BEM-style component classes, not utility stacks.**

This keeps the Shopify theme predictable, maintainable, and visually consistent with the React source.

---

## Why This Pattern Is Required

React projects often rely on utility-first styling (`md:`, `bg-[#...]`, `w-10`, etc.) that is tightly coupled to a build pipeline.

In Shopify:

- utility pipelines are usually not equivalent to the original React setup,
- Dawn defaults can override or conflict with custom layouts,
- styles can drift as sections change.

The Valgara Pattern solves this by enforcing:

- deterministic CSS ownership per component,
- explicit stylesheet inclusion per Liquid file,
- clear source-to-target traceability.

---

## Core Rules (Non-Negotiable)

## 1) No Tailwind Utility Leakage in Liquid

Remove utility classes from Liquid templates/snippets/sections, including patterns like:

- `md:`, `lg:`, `hover:`, `focus:`
- `bg-[#...]`, `text-[...]`, `w-[...]`, `h-[...]`
- utility-first spacing/layout chains (`flex`, `gap-*`, `rounded-*`) when used as direct conversion output

Replace with component-scoped classes.

## 2) Use Scoped BEM-Style Classes

Use a namespaced block and element structure:

- Block: `styledrop-product-card`
- Element: `styledrop-product-card__image`
- Modifier: `styledrop-product-card__image--active`

This prevents cross-section CSS collisions and mirrors component boundaries.

## 3) One Dedicated CSS Asset Per Converted Component

Each converted component must have:

- `assets/styledrop-[component-name].css`

Example:

- `snippets/product-card.liquid`
- `assets/styledrop-product-card.css`

## 4) Every Liquid File Must Include Its Component CSS

At the top of each converted Liquid file:

```liquid
{{ 'styledrop-[component-name].css' | asset_url | stylesheet_tag }}
```

No implicit dependency on global utility styles.

## 5) Preserve Shopify-Native Functionality

When refactoring classes, do not break:

- form actions and product/cart endpoints,
- Dawn/Shopify JS hooks required for behavior,
- IDs/data attributes used by scripts,
- section schema settings and block logic.

Valgara changes presentation architecture, not business logic.

## 6) Add Source Mapping Header

Each newly converted file should include a traceability header:

```liquid
{%- comment -%}
  Converted from: src/components/Example.tsx
{%- endcomment -%}
```

This supports audits and handovers.

---

## Recommended File Mapping Strategy

When converting one React component:

1. Identify source component and all visual states.
2. Create/adjust Liquid file (section/snippet/template).
3. Replace utility-heavy classes with BEM scoped classes.
4. Create/update `assets/styledrop-[component-name].css`.
5. Include the CSS asset in the Liquid file.
6. Keep all Shopify dynamic logic intact.
7. Validate responsive behavior and parity with React.

---

## Practical Example

### React/Tailwind style

```html
<div class="bg-[#0D0D0D] rounded-2xl p-4 md:p-6">
  <img class="w-full h-[320px] object-cover" />
</div>
```

### Valgara style in Liquid

```liquid
{{ 'styledrop-product-card.css' | asset_url | stylesheet_tag }}

<div class="styledrop-product-card">
  <img class="styledrop-product-card__image" />
</div>
```

### Component CSS

```css
.styledrop-product-card {
  background: #0d0d0d;
  border-radius: 1rem;
  padding: 1rem;
}

@media (min-width: 768px) {
  .styledrop-product-card {
    padding: 1.5rem;
  }
}

.styledrop-product-card__image {
  width: 100%;
  height: 320px;
  object-fit: cover;
}
```

Result: same visual outcome, but now fully isolated and Shopify-safe.

---

## Responsive and State Handling in Valgara

Do not encode responsive or state behavior as utility tokens in markup.

Use CSS and modifiers:

- responsive: media queries in `styledrop-[component].css`,
- state: `--active`, `--open`, `--selected` modifiers toggled by JS,
- variants: separate modifier classes, not inline utility combinations.

Example:

- `styledrop-filter-sidebar__group--open`
- `styledrop-product-gallery__dot--active`

---

## How Valgara Protects Visual Parity

Valgara improves parity by making style ownership explicit:

- React component -> Liquid file
- React style intent -> dedicated scoped CSS file
- Responsive states -> media queries and modifiers

This removes hidden styling dependencies and reduces regressions during future edits.

---

## Common Conversion Mistakes to Avoid

- Leaving Tailwind utility classes in Liquid after migration.
- Relying on `style-drop-custom.css` for component-specific layouts that should be isolated.
- Using Dawn `card-product` for custom converted surfaces where parity is required.
- Changing classes and accidentally breaking JS selectors used by cart, variants, or drawers.
- Creating CSS without namespacing, causing global overrides.

---

## Validation Checklist (Per File)

- [ ] `Converted from:` header added.
- [ ] Tailwind utility classes removed from markup.
- [ ] BEM-style scoped classes applied.
- [ ] Dedicated `styledrop-[component].css` exists.
- [ ] CSS asset is included via `stylesheet_tag`.
- [ ] Shopify functionality still works (cart, variants, forms, filters).
- [ ] Mobile and desktop parity checked against React source.

---

## Final Principle

For this project, **Valgara is not an optional style preference**.  
It is the required migration protocol to achieve stable, auditable, pixel-faithful React-to-Shopify conversion.

